import nltk
import urllib
from __future__ import division

import csv
from string import punctuation
files=['negative.txt','positive.txt','obama_tweets.txt']
path='http://www.unc.edu/~ncaren/haphazard/'
for file_name in files:
    urllib.urlretrieve(path+file_name,file_name)
tweets = open("empire.csv").read()

tweets_list = tweets.split('\n')



pos_sent = open("positive.txt").read()
positive_words=pos_sent.split('\n')
positive_counts=[]

neg_sent = open('negative.txt').read()
negative_words=neg_sent.split('\n')
negative_counts=[]
positive =[]
negative =[]
label=[]
pt=[]
ptr=[]

tweets_list = tweets_list[2:]
tweets_list = tweets_list[:-3]
for tweet in tweets_list:
    positive_counter=0
    negative_counter=0
    
    
    tweet_processed=tweet.lower()
    x = tweet_processed.find("rated")
    tweet_processed = tweet_processed[x+9:]
    x = tweet_processed.rfind("like")
    tweet_processed = tweet_processed[:x]
    y = tweet_processed.find("empire restaurant: dear")
    tweet_processed = tweet_processed[:y]
    print y,tweet_processed
   
    for p in list(punctuation):
        tweet_processed=tweet_processed.replace(p,'')
    
    tweet_processed=tweet_processed.strip()
    tweet_processed=' '.join(tweet_processed.split())
    words=tweet_processed.split(' ')
    
    word_count=len(words)
    pos_word=""
    neg_word=""
    for word in words:
        if word in positive_words:
            positive_counter=positive_counter+1
            pos_word=pos_word+", "+word
        elif word in negative_words:
            negative_counter=negative_counter+1
            neg_word=neg_word+", "+word
    positive.append(pos_word)
    negative.append(neg_word)
    positive_counts.append(positive_counter/word_count)
    negative_counts.append(negative_counter/word_count)
    pt.append(tweet_processed)
    if (positive_counter>negative_counter):
        label.append("positive")
        x = "positive"
    else: 
        label.append("negative")
        x = "negative"
    ptr = ptr +[(tweet_processed,x)]
print len(positive_counts)

#output=zip(tweets_list,positive_counts,negative_counts,positive,negative)
testfile = zip(pt,label)
writer = csv.writer(open('data.csv', 'wb'))
writer.writerows(testfile)

5213  this happens to be one of the most commonly visited restaurant by me in bangalore. i think the location of this place is absolutely perfect and also the quality in the restaurant is pretty good. it makes people easily come back again and again. situated in one cross away from jyothi nivas college and very easily locatable. this is one restaurant that surely has stood the test of time and has delivered the quality time and again. though it is one of the favourite places to visit of the non-veg eaters, i being a veggie, don’t mind going there coz whatever veg item they make there are pretty decent. i know that there quite a few of the my friends who say about the veg tasting good coz of the nv getting mixed into the veg food. but i know thats not true coz the taste is pretty much same as what you get a vegetarian place. the best thing about this restaurant are its - location, timing and consistency of food and price. location wise its just so close to forum mall that you would want to come grab a bide anytime after the movie. people visiting many pubs in and around koramangala can come over here. timing wise they are open until pretty late nearly 1am. i mean this surely is the current time but i still remember the times when there never used to be any restrictions in bangalore and the restaurant would be open until 2-2.30am or 3am or i think, i don’t remember exactly. but, yes this is one restaurant chain where is available when other would be shut down. consistency of the taste is also critical coz if the restaurant stops to take care of its customers coz of crowd then people usually stop going there. but, this place has maintained that. price is also pretty much reachable range. i mean, if you eat a wholesome veg meal among 2 people it might cost at max rs.600. with the quality they serve, it is quite worth it. now to talk more about the food. my favourite here happens to the ‘daal fry’ which is a simple yellow daal-subji which most of the times is a bit thick, but sometimes it might be little liquidy but the taste is fine. some of the times it might be on the spicier side as well but to most extent the taste is same. next item to write about this it the ‘paneer butter masala’, which is really decent coz of the thick tomato gravy served. many times, it might good option to hold the gravy and try with an evergreen item called ‘ghee rice’. i think everyone visiting empire here surely go for at least 1 place of ‘ghee rice’ :) then comes the other item ie., vegetarian kurma which is also decently done with good mix of masala. all of the above subjis goes best along with ‘wheat parata’ which is simply the thick form of ‘chapati’ and seriously it is super-awesome :)…i just love taking it. it does take some time to prepare and you need wait but its worth the wait. to write about few more items - ‘coin parata’, which is a small thick parata in the shape of coin. if you don’t like the oily ones, ‘tandori roti’ is decent which very little oil.   it wouldn’t be good if i don’t write about the ‘special raita’ which is usually available if you go there by close to 10-10.30pm. apart from these the other items that are decent to take include - biryani, lemon rice, appam with stew, green salad. and yes, you should not forget taking ‘sulemaan tea’ which is simple tea-with tea-bags dipped with sugar and lemon squeezed into it. its made quite easily and pretty good. especially when you want to bring down the hang-over :) i guess i spent enough time writing about this place. my overall rating for this place is 3.5. its surely a fair assessment coz i have visited this place loads of times and i would not have done that unless they maintained quality. i want to write a lot more but then it might be abit boring but yes i can go and on about this place. i guess it would be right unless i write about the crowd coz the crowd coming into this place is unbelievable - its posh, young, happenings, party-goers, families, friends, i mean good mix of people. cost of the food for 2 would be nearly rs.500-600 (for wholesome food) other ratings includes - food - 3.5/5 drinks - -1  probably the worst managed empire restaurant in the city. the food feels tasteless and the funny thing is no matter what gravy you order it all feels the same. the most convenient food joint though. late night and hungry? this is the place to go. parking is a big issue if you drive a car. weekends its packed but again mainly because there are no other options. chicken kababs are excellent. they have maintained quality in only two items i guess. these kababs and the ghee rice! the new alfaham chicken is good and tasty. a refreshing change in the otherwise mundane menu. grilled chicken is average. shawarma quantity is less but the taste is good. it gets 5 stars for convenience. but food wise has miles to go before it can improve.

-1  well... this review is only for the desserts at empire. being a veggie, i may not be the right one to comment on the food options at empire which is primarily famous for its dosa chicken. so, this one day after having spent a good evening at fenny's, we land up at empire to have a dessert. only reason: no other place is open in blr that late. the place is beaming with energy, alive and kicking. there is seating and a self service area which is open to the road. you could collect your kebabs/desserts and enjoy them while chatting away with your pals. so our yearning friend ordered the death by chocolate. we knew it wouldnt be anywhere close to corner house, but at least it would be a sundae. ended up being two tiny scoops of chocolate icecream topped with a little chocolate sauce served in a plastic container as big as the ones in which you collect your temple ""prasadam"". what a rip off i say!! and 195 bucks down the drain for this mess. to make things worse, the chocolate icecream seemed to have a strong orange flavour. i recollect that the desserts used to be good in the church street outlet. the average rating here speaks for itself. best to avoid it if you can! -1  empire's dosa chicken is one of my favorite. i went out with my cousin on a weekend to koramangala empire and i had already decided that i would order dosa chicken. i recommended the same to my cousin and he ordered it as well. for a price of rs. 120 per plate, you get 2 dosas along with spicy chicken curry. you could expect quality food for that price, however, for empire - especially the koramangala branch, it doesn't seem to matter. we placed our order and in about 5 minutes, it was ready and served. my cousin acknowledged that it was good and tasty enough. when i was about to finish my first dosa, i found a wired hair like structure in the curry. when i pulled it out, i was shocked and disgusted to see a dead cockroach in it :-/ i immediately took my plate and showed it to the person who served me and i could literally see the guilt on his face. he apologized to me and took away the plate from my hand. he offered me another plate, but i refused and demanded for a refund. he did a full refund on both the plates, but before doing that he dumped my plate in the dustbin, so that it doesn't turn out to a big issue. it was never expected from a restaurant which claims to offer international quality service. i have decided not to recommended this place to anyone else. rated   empire's dosa chicken is one of my favorite. i went out with my cousin on a weekend to koramangala empire and i had already decided that i would order dosa chicken. i recommended the same to my cousin and he ordered it as well. for a price of rs. 120 per plate, you get 2 dosas along with spicy chicken curry. you could expect quality food for that price, however, for empire - -1  bangalore, i'm here to set the record straight. i'll tell you what is up to snuff and what's in the rough. hotel empire international is a staple. and like all staples, it's there more likely because it has a special permit to stay open until 3am, and not really because their food is good. why make good food when you have no competition? see what i'm saying? prescription: i prescribe anything else on this block before 11pm. i also prescribe you not go out to eat after 11am, because being hungry is preferable than to forcing your non-sober mind to eat nasty dry chicken kabob, and terrible biryiani. once a rickshaw driver told me that they offered a sunday all you can eat brunch for 130 rs. i belived it because their food is so bad. verdict: the doctor is not in. (proceed at your own risk. or after 11pm. if you have to.)

-1  well the only reason i went to empire is that they are opened till late night. when you are searching for some late night food after a bar hopping trip or after a party around koramangala area, empire is the place to be. they have indoor sitting, but also some outdoor sitting area in the night. the place gets really crowded and the service can be really slow. better to try the fast food items here. i remember eating chicken dosa here, which sounds novel, and it tasted pretty well too.
-1  you should know what to order here; don't rely on waiters' suggestions! positives- +open till 2:00 am! +thali meal at a reasonable price negatives- -not really fast in service -not all waiters are 'friendly' as such -very few nice dishes on the menu must try- *chicken fried kebab *mutton raan *chicken alfaham *bheja fry and coin paratha *grilled chicken *ceylon parota *falooda what not to order - x butter chicken x chicken biryani x dosa chicken i have been here many times. one thing i'll tell you, 'hotel empire international' is completely overrated! the place is a bit unhygienic and unclean. their biryani is no good, and when you ask the waiter what their best dish is, he says butter chicken every time; and their butter chicken is not something you would want to waste your money on. please dont go by waiters' suggestions here as they suggest the most sub-par tasting dishes here. you must know exactly what to order here; everything else is not that good. what is really good is their chicken fried kebabs! really delicious! crisp on the outside and hot and tender on the inside with great flavour in the batter, the kebabs are an absolute must try. the grilled chicken is also really nice. the meat is cooked perfectly and the flavour of the marinade is great which makes it a good choice of order. the alfaham is worth a try as well. it has a good level of char on it that gives it a great taste. another thing that is a must try here is the mutton raan which is slow cooked motton leg; it has mild but great flavours. the mutton meat is tender from the slow roasting for hours. the bheja fry (mutton brain) with coin parathas are something different you rarely get anywhere else and is well cooked. their afternoon non-vegetarian thali is a huge steal! you get a pretty good variety of dishes like chicken and mutton gravies, chilly chicken and chicken kebab, with dal, veg sabjis, rice, coin parotas, sweet and pepsi or ice tea, all at a very reasonable price. the 'dosa chicken' which empire is oh so famous for, is just a huge joke! the dosas are always undercooked and taste of raw dosa batter and the chicken gravy taste sub-par. just not worth wasting your money and appetite on. the shawarmas are available in spicy and regular types; but both varieties taste average. nothing about it that's really great. the shawarmas are completely overpriced here at nearly a 100 rupees. trust me, it's not worth your money or your appetite. empire is a good place for food as long as you know what to order! -1  koramangala is the melting pot for food lovers and the area around jyothi nivas is no exception. empire koramangala is located at the heart of this fast emerging food hub. the streets are buzzing with activity during late evening and by flooded with vehicles and people during late hours. empire offers a quick street side self service counter at the ground floor in front the hotel and the dine in restaurant is one level above. shawarma rolls sell by hundreds here everyday. the self service counter has all the typical empire entrees like grilled chicken, idli chicken, dosa chicken, sandwiches and icecreams. the dine has more variety of stuff and my personal favourite is the grilled chicken minus the color. the tandoori items are ok. parathas go well with the greasy chicken gravies. one of my favourite is the hyderabadi boneless chicken. the spl. dal fry with egg is very unique and goes well with the wheat parathas. there aren't many options for vegetarians. ambiance - -1  yes, you'd have to wait a long time to get your order, but thankfully we parcelled the food home. empire, as everyone says, is a landmark in koramangala. i've had food thrice here and all had been late nights. :) it's always jam packed with people waiting to have food here. they are famous for their kerala parota with butter chicken curry and this has never been a let down as far as i'm concerned. anyway, we ordered ghee rice, dal fry, mutton pepper dry, chicken kababs and butter chicken curry for take-away the other night. all the dishes were decent and so were the portions. that night being a friend's birthday, we wanted some dessert at the last minute. what's surprising is that we got a whole caramel custard (the size of a standard plate) and this was really delicious! can't fault it at all. :) late nights and hunger will probably get you here, and i'm sure empire will remain open for that very reason.

In [110]:
def get_word_features(wordlist):
    wordlist = nltk.FreqDist(wordlist)
    word_features = wordlist.keys()
    return word_features
In [111]:
def get_words_in_tweets(tweets):
    all_words = []
    for (words, sentiment) in tweets:
      all_words.extend(words)
    return all_words
In [112]:
word_features = get_word_features(get_words_in_tweets(tweets))
In [113]:
def extract_features(document):
    document_words = set(document)
    features = {}
    for word in word_features:
        features['contains(%s)' % word] = (word in document_words)
    return features
In [114]:
training_set = nltk.classify.apply_features(extract_features, tweets)
